\layout SubSection

Current work (March 2002)
\layout Standard

Daniel Lemire is currently doing research on data thinning and Computer
 Aided Geometric Design (CAGD) at Acadia University.
 He has worked for years experience in telehealth and data processing.
 He is currently interested in building efficient summaries for large XML
 files and helping data mining applications scale better on large databases
 through data thinning.
\layout Standard

Among his recent contributions to CAGD is his work on High Resolution Subdivisio
n Schemes 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{key-56}

\end_inset 

.
 The purpose of this work is to propose and study a new truly local data
 interpolation scheme which can be one order of magnitude better at approximatin
g polynomials than the existing schemes in some cases.
 Among applications of such work are pyramidal transforms which can be used
 for efficient progressive data transfers and analysis.
\layout SubSection

Hermite Subdivision Schemes (2000-2001)
\layout Standard

Hermite Subdivision Schemes are a CAGD and data processing technique.
 Daniel Lemire's work 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{key-57}

\end_inset 

 has lead to a new type of mathematical analysis for the regularity of Hermite
 Subdivision Schemes based on the Fourier transform.
\layout Standard

Citation: S.
